{"add":{"doc":{"id":"2c25b860b972391d51cbbaf805fb774fe355a692d2a77120d663b7d5df128846","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/98/A_South_Sudanese_girl_at_independence_festivities_%285926735716%29.jpg/220px-A_South_Sudanese_girl_at_independence_festivities_%285926735716%29.jpg","previous":[],"after":["Between 9 and 15 January 2011, a referendum was held to determine whether South Sudan should become an independent country and separate from Sudan. 98.83% of the population voted for independence.[25] Those living in the north and expatriates living overseas also voted.[26] South Sudan formally became independent from Sudan on 9 July, although certain disputes still remained, including the division of oil revenues, as 75% of all the former Sudan's oil reserves are in South Sudan.[27] The region of Abyei still remains disputed and a separate referendum will be held in Abyei on whether they want to join Sudan or South Sudan.[28] The South Kordofan conflict broke out in June 2011 between the Army of Sudan and the SPLA over the Nuba Mountains."]}}}